⸻

1. Start with the constraint

For any circle:

C = 2\pi r

If we set the circumference equal to π:

2\pi r = \pi

Solve for r:

r = \tfrac{1}{2}

So the circle becomes:
	•	Radius: r = 1/2
	•	Diameter: d = 1

Already interesting:
the diameter becomes exactly 1.

This makes the circle a natural unit-diameter circle.

⸻

2. Area becomes very simple

Area of a circle:

A = \pi r^2

Substitute r = 1/2:

A = \pi \left(\tfrac12\right)^2

A = \tfrac{\pi}{4}

So we get:

Property	Value
Circumference	π
Diameter	1
Radius	1/2
Area	π/4


⸻

3. The arc-length interpretation becomes elegant

Arc length formula:

s = r\theta

Since r = 1/2:

s = \tfrac12 \theta

So:

\theta = 2s

Meaning:

angle = twice the arc length

That is a very clean linear relationship.

Example:

arc length	angle
0.1	0.2 rad
0.5	1 rad
1	2 rad

So arc measurement becomes extremely convenient.

⸻

4. It normalizes the sine/cosine geometry

Coordinates on the circle:

(x,y) = (\tfrac12 \cos\theta, \tfrac12 \sin\theta)

This means the circle is simply a scaled unit circle.

Many trigonometric integrals simplify nicely.

