9. A deeper geometric observation

If circumference = π then

\text{area} = \frac{C^2}{4\pi}

Substitute C = \pi:

A = \frac{\pi^2}{4\pi}

A = \frac{\pi}{4}

So the circle’s area becomes directly determined by circumference squared with minimal constants.

This is the general isoperimetric equality case.

